@startuml Unix Socket vs TCP Socket
title Unix Socket vs TCP Socket — Side by Side

skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam BoxPadding 10
skinparam NoteBackgroundColor #FFFACD
skinparam NoteBorderColor #DAA520

== TCP Socket (network) ==

actor "Client\n(browser)" as Client1

box "Machine A" #LightBlue
    participant "Nginx\n:80" as Nginx1
end box

box "Machine A or B" #LightGreen
    participant "Go App\n:8080" as GoTCP
end box

Client1 -> Nginx1: GET / HTTP/1.1
Nginx1 -> GoTCP: proxy_pass\nhttp://localhost:8080\n(goes through network stack)
GoTCP --> Nginx1: HTTP response
Nginx1 --> Client1: HTTP/1.1 200 OK

note over Nginx1, GoTCP
  TCP: data travels through
  full network stack even on
  the same machine.
  Identifier: IP:PORT
end note

== Unix Socket (same machine only) ==

actor "Client\n(browser)" as Client2

box "Same Machine — OS Kernel" #LightCoral
    participant "Nginx\n:80" as Nginx2
    participant "Kernel\nIPC Buffer" as Kernel
    participant "Go App\n(no port)" as GoUnix
end box

participant "/run/myapp.sock\n(socket file)" as SockFile

Client2 -> Nginx2: GET / HTTP/1.1

Nginx2 -> SockFile: connect to\n/run/myapp.sock
SockFile -> Kernel: OS routes through\ninternal IPC buffer
Kernel -> GoUnix: deliver request\n(no network stack)
GoUnix -> GoUnix: execute handler\ndoSomeWork()
GoUnix --> Kernel: write response\nto IPC buffer
Kernel --> Nginx2: response delivered\nthrough socket file
Nginx2 --> Client2: HTTP/1.1 200 OK

note over Nginx2, GoUnix
  Unix socket: data never
  leaves the kernel.
  Faster + no port exposed.
  Identifier: /run/myapp.sock
end note

@enduml

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

@startuml Unix Socket Nginx Go App
title Unix Socket — Nginx forwarding request to Go App

skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam BoxPadding 10
skinparam NoteBackgroundColor #FFFACD
skinparam NoteBorderColor #DAA520

actor "Client" as Client

box "Network" #LightYellow
    participant "Port 80\n(public)" as Port
end box

box "Same Machine — OS" #LightBlue
    participant "Nginx" as Nginx
    participant "/run/myapp.sock\n(socket file)" as Sock
    participant "Go App\n(no port exposed)" as Go
end box

note over Port
  Only port 80 is
  exposed to the outside.
  Go app has no open port.
end note

Client -> Port: GET /hello HTTP/1.1
Port -> Nginx: incoming connection

note over Nginx
  nginx.conf:
  location / {
    proxy_pass http://unix:/run/myapp.sock;
  }
end note

Nginx -> Sock: write request bytes\nto socket file
activate Sock
Sock -> Go: OS delivers bytes\nvia kernel IPC buffer
activate Go

note over Go
  Go code:
  listener, _ := net.Listen("unix", "/run/myapp.sock")
  http.HandleFunc("/hello", helloHandler)
  http.Serve(listener, nil)
end note

Go -> Go: helloHandler() triggered\n→ doSomeWork()\n→ return "Hello World"

Go --> Sock: write response bytes\nback to socket
deactivate Go
Sock --> Nginx: OS delivers response\nto nginx
deactivate Sock

Nginx --> Port: HTTP/1.1 200 OK\n"Hello World"
Port --> Client: HTTP/1.1 200 OK\n"Hello World"

note over Client, Go
  Key points:
  - Go app never opens a TCP port
  - Communication stays inside the OS kernel
  - /run/myapp.sock is just an address, not a real file
  - Faster than TCP because no network stack traversal
end note

@enduml